WHEREAS, baptized in the Obion River at the age of twelve, Mrs. Chatman was not
content to concern herself merely with this world but thought much of the next, and she was an
active member of Nashville First Baptist Church, a faithful and loving soul to the last; and
WHEREAS, she is still fondly remembered by her nephew, Tony (Becki) McGehee; her
great nieces, Meagan (Cason) Short and Rachel (Stan) Revelle; her great-nephew, David
Kenney; her lifelong "family" members, John McCullough and Albert Marsh; and her godson,
Guy Marsh; and
WHEREAS, in addition to her parents, she was preceded in death by her siblings, Annie
Lee, JD, Leroy, Alberta, and Maddie Joyce, and her beloved niece, Catherine Kenney; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Chatman was an exemplary public servant and consummate
professional who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for her fellow citizens in
numerous capacities; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Gladys Maurine Chatman,
reflecting fondly upon her impeccable character and her stalwart commitment to living the
examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mrs. Chatman.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
